 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a0b1c2d3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# LSTM Advanced Model for Sarcasm Detection\n",
    "\n",
    "## Objective\n",
    "The goal of this notebook is to build an advanced deep learning model to automatically detect sarcasm in Reddit comments. Sarcasm detection is formulated as a **supervised binary text classification** task, where:\n",
    "- **Label 1** = the comment is sarcastic\n",
    "- **Label 0** = the comment is not sarcastic\n",
    "\n",
    "Unlike the baseline models (Logistic Regression and SVM) which rely on TF-IDF word frequency features, the LSTM model reads the comment **word by word sequentially**, allowing it to capture the order of words and the context of the conversation. This is especially important for sarcasm, which often depends on how something is said rather than which words are used.\n",
    "\n",
    "## What I Did\n",
    "I implemented a Long Short-Term Memory (LSTM) neural network using the combined text of each Reddit comment and its parent comment as input. The pipeline consists of the following steps:\n",
    "1. Load pre-split train and test datasets (807,972 training samples, 201,992 test samples)\n",
    "2. Combine comment and parent comment into a single text field to capture conversational context\n",
    "3. Tokenize the text into word indices using the top 10,000 most common words\n",
    "4. Pad all sequences to a fixed length of 100 words\n",
    "5. Build a Sequential LSTM model with an Embedding layer, LSTM layer, Dropout, and sigmoid output\n",
    "6. Train the model with early stopping (patience=3) to prevent overfitting\n",
    "7. Evaluate on the test set using Accuracy and F1 Score\n",
    "\n",
    "The LSTM model achieved a **test accuracy of 70.79%** and an **F1 score of 0.7046**, outperforming all baseline models."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a1b2c3d4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 1. Import required libraries"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c3d4e5f6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.text import Tokenizer       # convert text to sequences of word indices\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras.preprocessing.sequence import pad_sequences # pad sequences to fixed length\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential                   # stack layers sequentially\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras.layers import Embedding, LSTM, Dense, Dropout # model layers\n",
    "from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ModelCheckpoint # training callbacks\n",
    "from sklearn.metrics import (accuracy_score, f1_score,\n",
    "                             confusion_matrix, classification_report) # performance metrics"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d4e5f6a7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 2. Load datasets"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "e5f6a7b8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "train = pd.read_csv(\"C:/Users/zacky/Desktop/machine learning/archive/final train test data/sarcasm_train.csv\")\n",
    "test  = pd.read_csv(\"C:/Users/zacky/Desktop/machine learning/archive/final train test data/sarcasm_test.csv\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Data loaded successfully. Training set size: {len(train)}, Test set size: {len(test)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f6a7b8c9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 3. Prepare combined text and labels"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "a7b8c9d0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Create combined text if not already in the file\n",
    "# We combine comment + parent_comment to capture conversational context\n",
    "if \"combined_text\" not in train.columns:\n",
    "    train[\"combined_text\"] = train[\"comment\"] + \" \" + train[\"parent_comment\"]\n",
    "    test[\"combined_text\"]  = test[\"comment\"]  + \" \" + test[\"parent_comment\"]\n",
    "    print(\"Combined text created!\")\n",
    "else:\n",
    "    print(\"Combined text already exists!\")\n",
    "\n",
    "X_train = train[\"combined_text\"]\n",
    "X_test  = test[\"combined_text\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "y_train = train[\"label\"].values\n",
    "y_test  = test[\"label\"].values\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show class balance — should be ~50/50 for balanced dataset\n",
    "print(\"\\nClass balance in train:\")\n",
    "print(pd.Series(y_train).value_counts(normalize=True).round(3))\n",
    "print(\"\\nClass balance in test:\")\n",
    "print(pd.Series(y_test).value_counts(normalize=True).round(3))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b8c9d0e1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 4. Tokenize the text"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c9d0e1f2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "vocab_size = 10000   # keep only the top 10000 most common words\n",
    "\n",
    "# Fit tokenizer on TRAIN only to prevent data leakage into the test set\n",
    "tokenizer = Tokenizer(num_words=vocab_size, oov_token=\"<OOV>\")\n",
    "tokenizer.fit_on_texts(X_train)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Convert text to sequences of word indices\n",
    "train_seq = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_train)\n",
    "test_seq  = tokenizer.texts_to_sequences(X_test)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Vocabulary size:\", len(tokenizer.word_index))\n",
    "print(\"Example sequence:\", train_seq[0][:10], \"...\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d0e1f2a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 5. Pad sequences to fixed length"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "e1f2a3b4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "maxlen = 100   # max words per comment — shorter comments get padded, longer ones get truncated\n",
    "\n",
    "train_pad = pad_sequences(train_seq, maxlen=maxlen,\n",
    "                          padding=\"post\", truncating=\"post\")\n",
    "test_pad  = pad_sequences(test_seq,  maxlen=maxlen,\n",
    "                          padding=\"post\", truncating=\"post\")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Train padded shape:\", train_pad.shape)\n",
    "print(\"Test padded shape:\", test_pad.shape)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f2a3b4c5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 6. Build the LSTM model"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "a3b4c5d6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "model = Sequential([\n",
    "    Embedding(input_dim    = vocab_size,  # vocabulary size — number of unique words\n",
    "              output_dim   = 128,          # embedding dimensions — each word becomes a 128-dim vector\n",
    "              input_length = maxlen),      # sequence length\n",
    "\n",
    "    LSTM(units=64, return_sequences=False),# LSTM layer — reads the sequence and builds understanding\n",
    "    Dropout(0.5),                          # randomly drop 50% of neurons to prevent overfitting\n",
    "\n",
    "    Dense(units=1, activation=\"sigmoid\")  # output layer — predicts probability of sarcasm (0 or 1)\n",
    "])\n",
    "\n",
    "model.compile(\n",
    "    optimizer = \"adam\",\n",
    "    loss      = \"binary_crossentropy\",    # loss function for binary classification\n",
    "    metrics   = [\"accuracy\"]\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "model.summary()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b4c5d6e7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 7. Train the LSTM model with early stopping"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "c5d6e7f8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Early stopping — stops training when val_loss stops improving\n",
    "# patience=3 because the model takes ~3 epochs to start learning\n",
    "early_stop = EarlyStopping(\n",
    "    monitor              = \"val_loss\",\n",
    "    patience             = 3,             # stop after 3 bad epochs\n",
    "    restore_best_weights = True,          # revert to best epoch automatically\n",
    "    verbose              = 1\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Model checkpoint — saves the best model weights to a file automatically\n",
    "checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(\n",
    "    filepath       = \"best_lstm_model.keras\",\n",
    "    monitor        = \"val_loss\",          # save when val_loss improves\n",
    "    save_best_only = True,\n",
    "    verbose        = 1\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Early stopping : ON (patience=3)\")\n",
    "print(\"Model checkpoint: ON (saves best_lstm_model.keras)\")\n",
    "print(\"Starting training...\\n\")\n",
    "\n",
    "history = model.fit(\n",
    "    train_pad, y_train,\n",
    "    epochs           = 10,\n",
    "    batch_size       = 32,\n",
    "    validation_split = 0.2,              # use 20% of training data for validation\n",
    "    callbacks        = [early_stop, checkpoint],\n",
    "    verbose          = 1\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "best_epoch = np.argmin(history.history[\"val_loss\"]) + 1\n",
    "print(f\"\\nBest epoch      : {best_epoch}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Best val_loss   : {min(history.history['val_loss']):.4f}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Best val_accuracy: {max(history.history['val_accuracy']):.4f}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d6e7f8a9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 8. Evaluate model performance"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "e7f8a9b0",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Predict on the test set — threshold at 0.5 to convert probability to label\n",
    "predictions = (model.predict(test_pad) > 0.5).astype(int).flatten()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Accuracy\n",
    "accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, predictions)\n",
    "print(f\"Test Accuracy : {accuracy:.4f}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# F1 Score\n",
    "f1 = f1_score(y_test, predictions)\n",
    "print(f\"F1 Score      : {f1:.4f}\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Full classification report — shows precision, recall, F1 per class\n",
    "print(\"\\nClassification Report:\")\n",
    "print(classification_report(y_test, predictions,\n",
    "      target_names=[\"Not Sarcastic (0)\", \"Sarcastic (1)\"]))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Confusion Matrix — rows = actual, columns = predicted\n",
    "print(\"Confusion Matrix:\")\n",
    "print(confusion_matrix(y_test, predictions))\n",
    "print(\"(Rows = Actual, Columns = Predicted)\")"
   ]
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f8a9b0c1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### 9. Summary and Potential Improvements\n",
    "\n",
    "## Results Summary\n",
    "| Model | Accuracy | F1 Score |\n",
    "|---|---|---|\n",
    "| Majority Vote | 49.8% | 0.33 |\n",
    "| SVM (LinearSVC) | 66.0% | 0.66 |\n",
    "| Logistic Regression | 67.1% | 0.67 |\n",
    "| LSTM (no early stopping) | 69.6% | 0.69 |\n",
    "| **LSTM (with early stopping)** | **70.8%** | **0.70** |\n",
    "\n",
    "## What Can Be Improved\n",
    "\n",
    "**1. Increase Vocabulary Size**\n",
    "The current vocabulary is capped at 10,000 words, but the full dataset contains over 288,000 unique words. Expanding to 20,000–30,000 words would allow the model to capture more meaningful and rare sarcasm-related terms.\n",
    "\n",
    "**2. Better Text Preprocessing Before Tokenization**\n",
    "Currently the raw text is fed directly into the tokenizer without cleaning. Adding lowercasing, URL removal, and punctuation stripping before tokenization would reduce vocabulary noise and give the model cleaner, more consistent input.\n",
    "\n",
    "**3. Increase Sequence Length**\n",
    "The current maximum sequence length is 100 words. Since Reddit comments and parent comments combined can be much longer, increasing maxlen to 150 or 200 would preserve more context that the model currently loses by truncation.\n",
    "\n",
    "**4. Use Pre-trained GloVe Embeddings**\n",
    "Instead of learning embeddings from scratch, using pre-trained GloVe vectors (e.g., glove.6B.100d) would give the model a head start by initializing word vectors with meanings already learned from a large external corpus.\n",
    "\n",
    "**5. Add a Second LSTM Layer or Use Bidirectional LSTM**\n",
    "A second stacked LSTM layer or a Bidirectional LSTM would allow the model to read the text both forward and backward, capturing patterns that a single-direction LSTM might miss — particularly useful for sarcasm which often depends on the ending of a sentence.\n",
    "\n",
    "**6. Add Random Seed for Reproducibility**\n",
    "The current model initializes with random weights, so results differ slightly between runs. Adding fixed random seeds would make the results consistent and reproducible.\n",
    "\n",
    "```python\n",
    "import random, tensorflow as tf\n",
    "random.seed(42)\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "tf.random.set_seed(42)\n",
    "```"
   ]
  }
 ],
